its while on remand</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re on remand, you can&rsquo;t claim: </p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Job Seeker’s Allowance</li>\n  <li>Income Support - apart from <a href=\"/benefits-and-prison/support-for-mortgage-interest\" title=\"What help can you get with housing costs\">help with housing costs</a> </li>\n  <li>Pension Credit - apart from <a href=\"/benefits-and-prison/support-for-mortgage-interest\" title=\"What help can you get with housing costs\">help with housing costs</a> </li>\n  <li>Working Tax Credit - although your partner may be able to <a href=\"/benefits-and-prison/tax-credits\" title=\"Claiming for an absent partner\">claim for an absent partner</a></li>\n  <li>Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit</li>\n  <li>Incapacity Benefit</li>\n  <li>Employment and Support Allowance</li>\n  <li>Attendance Allowance</li>\n  <li>Disability Living Allowance</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>You won&rsquo;t be entitled to Statutory Sick Pay or Statutory Maternity Pay from your employer.</p>\n\n<h2>Benefit arrears</h2>\n\n<p>If you are owed any benefit arrears at the time you&rsquo;re sent to prison or on remand, you can make a request in writing for these to be paid to someone else.</p>\n\n<h3>Benefit arrears if you&rsquo;re not convicted</h3>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re not convicted, you can get benefit arrears for:</p>\n\n<ul>\n  <li>Contributory Employment and Support Allowance </li>\n  <li>Incapacity Benefit</li>\n</ul>\n\n<h3>Benefit arrears if you&rsquo;re convicted</h3>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re sent to prison and claim Industrial Injuries Disablement Benefit, you may be entitled to up to a year&rsquo;s arrears whenever you&rsquo;re released.</p>\n\n<h2>Claiming benefits on release</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re entitled to benefits, you can put in new claims as soon as you leave prison. You may also be able to get \n<a href=\"/leaving-prison/support-when-someone-leaves-prison\" title=\"Find out what support there is\">other financial and practical support</a>.</p>\n\n<div class=