, you may be able to claim it instead. You may need to have your name added to the tenancy agreement, if it&rsquo;s not there already.</p>\n\n<h3>If your child is in prison</h3>\n\n<p>If your child goes to prison, you&rsquo;ll need to contact your local council to see if your Housing Benefit entitlement will change. For example, if you rent from a private landlord, the amount of benefit paid is limited, depending on who&rsquo;s living with you.</p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/benefits-and-prison/council-tax-benefit","slug":"council-tax-benefit","order":4,"title":"Council Tax Benefit","body":"<p>If you&rsquo;re in prison or on remand you won&rsquo;t count as an adult living in a property for Council Tax. </p>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re single</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re single and in prison or on remand and there’s no one living in your home, you can apply for it to be exempt from Council Tax. </p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Your home won’t be exempt if you’re in prison for not paying Council Tax or a fine for not paying it.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re in a couple</h2>\n\n<h3>On remand</h3>\n\n<p>If your partner’s on remand and is expected home in a year or less, you can claim or continue to claim joint Council Tax Benefit for up to 52 weeks.</p>\n\n<h3>In prison</h3>\n\n<p>If your partner’s expected to be in prison for 13 weeks or less – including any time on remand, you can claim or continue to claim joint Council Tax Benefit for up to 13 weeks.</p>\n\n<h3>Making a new claim</h3>\n\n<p>If your partner’s going to be absent for more than 13 weeks and you&rsquo;re the only adult in the property, you&rsquo;ll get a 25% discount off your Council Tax bill. You may also be able to make a single claim for Council Tax Benefit. </p>\n\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/benefits-and-prison/tax-credits","slug":"tax-credits","order":5,"title":"Tax Credits","body":"<h2>Working Tax Credit</h2>\n\n<h3>If you&rsquo;re single</h3>\n\n<p>Your Wor